- Updated understanding: Telegram WebApp initData validation should use URL-decoded params (via parse_qsl) for data_check_string; parse_init_data now uses parse_qsl and json.loads directly on decoded user/chat fields.

## JWT & Authentication System
- JWT_SECRET is now the primary env var for JWT signing (falls back to ENCRYPTION_KEY for backward compatibility)
- In production, JWT_SECRET or ENCRYPTION_KEY MUST be set or the app will fail to start
- Development uses a fallback "dev-jwt-secret-do-not-use-in-production" key
- JWT tokens are created in /auth/token endpoint and validated via get_current_user dependency

## Bot Configuration
- BOT_USERNAME env var controls "Add to Group" links (defaults to "nexusbot")
- Public config endpoint at GET /api/v1/config returns {bot_username, environment}
- Mini App fetches bot username dynamically via getPublicConfig() in api/config.ts

## ID Handling
- Telegram IDs can exceed JavaScript's Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER (2^53-1)
- Backend uses BigInteger for telegram_id fields
- Frontend converts Telegram IDs to Database Group IDs via /groups/by-telegram-id/{telegram_id}
- Mini App routes use database Group IDs (not Telegram IDs)

## WebSocket Auth
- WebSocket connections at /ws/{group_id} accept token via query param
- Authentication happens during connect() - user_id param sets authenticated flag
- Commands require client.authenticated = true

## Critical Files
- api/routers/auth.py: JWT creation/validation, initData verification
- api/routers/admin.py: Public config endpoint
- mini-app/src/api/config.ts: Frontend config fetching
- mini-app/src/api/client.ts: Axios interceptor adds Bearer token

